# Unit Test Delegation Workflow

## When to Use

- A new feature, bug fix, or refactor requires unit tests to be created or updated.
- An existing test file needs to be extended to cover new behavior.
- Any task that includes a test-writing step — delegate it rather than writing tests inline.

## Core Rules

- Do **not** write unit tests inline in the main context. Delegate to a focused sub-context or sub-agent invocation.
- Always send a complete delegation brief — never just "add tests".
- Happy-path-only coverage is **not acceptable** when error paths, side effects, boundary values, or security-sensitive misuse paths exist.
- **Model note:** Cursor does not support per-rule model assignment. Model selection is global in Cursor Settings — prefer a lower-cost model (Flash/Haiku tier) when test delegation is the primary task.
- The main agent reviews sub-agent output and must challenge weak coverage or incorrect mock patterns.

## Workflow

1. Identify the files under test and the behaviors that need coverage.
2. Build a delegation brief containing:
   - Source file path(s) and test file path(s)
   - Behavior matrix: happy path, error path, side effects, boundary values, security-sensitive paths
   - Project name (backend / myorganizer / web-ui / auth / vault-core / web-vault / web-vault-ui / web-pages/<route>)
   - Any project-specific mocking constraints (Prisma, API client, Next.js router, vault)
3. Delegate to `TestScaffold` with the full brief.
4. Review the output against the checklist below.
5. If coverage gaps remain, send a targeted refinement request back to `TestScaffold`.
6. Accept only when all meaningful behavior paths are covered.

## Review Checklist

- [ ] Each important behavior has a concrete assertion (not just `toBeTruthy`)
- [ ] Negative / error paths are covered, not only success flows
- [ ] Side effects and call contracts are asserted (`toHaveBeenCalledWith`)
- [ ] Boundary values and invalid inputs are exercised
- [ ] Security-sensitive paths (auth bypass, unsafe input, secret leakage) are tested when in scope
- [ ] Mocks are deterministic, minimal, and match existing project patterns

